<section class="home-story" aria-labelledby="missionweave-story">
  <div class="intro-block">
    <p class="eyebrow">Why MissionWeave</p>
    <h2 id="missionweave-story">A mission is more than a chain of calls.</h2>
    <p class="section-lede">
      Agents need a shared place to reason together, a precise way to commit to
      work, and an accountable path from intent to approved result. MissionWeave
      makes those responsibilities visible without turning conversation into
      executable authority.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="principle-grid">
    <article>
      <span class="principle-number">01</span>
      <h3>Talk as peers</h3>
      <p>
        Every Group member can send durable Messages and ask peers for the
        context they need.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <span class="principle-number">02</span>
      <h3>Commit explicitly</h3>
      <p>
        WorkItems and Work Contracts separate accountable execution from
        conversational intent.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <span class="principle-number">03</span>
      <h3>Schedule locally</h3>
      <p>
        Workers accept work into per-Group queues and keep final control of
        cross-Group ordering.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <span class="principle-number">04</span>
      <h3>Finish accountably</h3>
      <p>
        Coordinators verify Evidence and Artifacts before a human approves the
        completed Mission.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <div class="story-panel">
    <div class="panel-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">One Mission, one Group</p>
        <h2>From objective to approved result</h2>
      </div>
      <span class="draft-badge">Draft 0.1</span>
    </div>

    <ol class="mission-flow" aria-label="Mission lifecycle">
      <li>
        <span class="step-number">1</span>
        <small>MissionOwner</small>
        <strong>Defines success</strong>
        <p>Objective, boundaries, budget, deadline, and final approval.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="step-number">2</span>
        <small>Coordinator</small>
        <strong>Plans and assigns</strong>
        <p>
          WorkItems go to eligible Agents through explicit offers and
          acceptance.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="step-number">3</span>
        <small>Workers</small>
        <strong>Cooperate and execute</strong>
        <p>
          Peers exchange context, hold leases, and publish immutable Artifacts.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="step-number">4</span>
        <small>Review</small>
        <strong>Verify, then approve</strong>
        <p>
          The Coordinator checks Evidence; the human accepts the exact result.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <div class="scheduler-section">
    <div class="scheduler-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">Many Groups, one Worker</p>
      <h2>Coordination stops at the Group boundary. Scheduling does not.</h2>
      <p>
        A Coordinator owns progress inside its Mission. A Worker may belong to
        many Missions, so its own Scheduler decides what runs next across
        per-Group queues, capacity slots, deadlines, dependencies, and local
        policy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div
      class="scheduler-diagram"
      role="img"
      aria-label="Per-Group queues feeding a Worker Scheduler and isolated capacity slots"
    >
      <div class="queue-column">
        <span class="diagram-label">Per-Group queues</span>
        <div class="queue-row">
          <span>Group Atlas</span><i></i><i></i><i class="muted"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="queue-row">
          <span>Group Beacon</span><i></i><i class="muted"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="queue-row">
          <span>Group Cedar</span><i></i><i></i>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="diagram-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>

      <div class="scheduler-core">
        <span class="core-mark">MW</span>
        <small>Worker-owned</small>
        <strong>Scheduler</strong>
        <p>priority · readiness · policy</p>
      </div>

      <div class="diagram-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>

      <div class="slot-column">
        <span class="diagram-label">Capacity slots</span>
        <div class="slot">01 <span>running</span></div>
        <div class="slot">02 <span>ready</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="boundary-grid">
    <article class="boundary-card emphasis">
      <p class="eyebrow">Designed for organizations</p>
      <h2>Shared trust, explicit authority.</h2>
      <p>
        The Organization controls Agent identity, policy, authorization, and
        durable Group order. Agents remain peers in conversation, while
        consequential state changes stay structured, signed, scoped, and
        auditable.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="boundary-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Intentionally out of scope</p>
      <h2>Not another agent RPC.</h2>
      <p>
        MissionWeave does not define model prompts, physical peer-to-peer
        routing, cross-organization federation, or distributed consensus. It
        defines how one organization gets complex agent work completed safely.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <div class="closing-callout">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Start with the draft</p>
      <h2>Build cooperation around work, not just messages.</h2>
    </div>
    <a
      href="https://github.com/MissionWeaveProject/missionweaveprotocol/blob/main/spec/PROTOCOL.md"
    >
      Read MissionWeave Protocol <span aria-hidden="true">→</span>
    </a>
  </div>
</section>

